paragraphs.title: Introduction
paragraphs.text:
%md
## Introduction
<h4>
 This notebook demonstrates an example of using ML to predict a handwritten number using the MNIST data set. This is done by leveraging the TensorFLow Python package which comes pre-installed in Zepl's default images along with the Python interpreter. Additional interpreters such as Scala, R and SQL are also provided as well as modules and packages such as Pandas, Numpy and scikit-learn.

 This notebook shows you how to:

* Run TensorFlow's basic tutorial on MNIST data using Softmax Regression
* Create an HTML canvas to get handwritten digit data from user input
* Predict the handwritten digit with a trained model

 Take a look at the [MNIST For ML Beginners](https://www.tensorflow.org/get_started/mnist/beginners) site for a detailed description of TensorFlow code.
 
 *Some code in this notebook is taken from [Tensorflow project](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow) under [Apache 2.0 License](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/LICENSE).*

paragraphs.title: Build a Softmax Regression Model
paragraphs.text: %python # The code below is from: # https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/examples/tutorials/mnist/mnist_softmax.py import tensorflow as tf # Create the model x = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, 784]) W = tf.Variable(tf.zeros([784, 10])) b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros([10])) y = tf.matmul(x, W) + b # Define loss and optimizer y_ = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, 10]) cross_entropy = tf.reduce_mean(tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits_v2(labels=y_, logits=y)) train_step = tf.train.GradientDescentOptimizer(0.5).minimize(cross_entropy) # Initialize Variables sess = tf.InteractiveSession() tf.global_variables_initializer().run() # Train the model for _ in range(1000): batch_xs, batch_ys = mnist.train.next_batch(100) sess.run(train_step, feed_dict={x: batch_xs, y_: batch_ys}) # Evaluate trained model correct_prediction = tf.equal(tf.argmax(y, 1), tf.argmax(y_, 1)) accuracy = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(correct_prediction, tf.float32)) # print the accuracy print('%html Accuracy = {0:.3f}'.format(sess.run(accuracy, feed_dict={x: mnist.test.images, y_: mnist.test.labels}))) #sess.close()
